context: <a0_0>The law of civil procedure<a0_0/> governs process in all judicial proceedings involving lawsuits between private parties. <b5_0>Traditional common law pleading<b5_0/> was replaced by <a1_0>code pleading<a1_0/> in <b6_0>24<b6_0/> states after <b7_0>New York<b7_0/> enacted the Field Code in 1850 and code pleading in turn was subsequently replaced again in most states by <a2_0>modern notice pleading<a2_0/> during the <a3_0>20th century<a3_0/>. <a4_0>The old English division between <b9_0>common law and equity courts<b9_0/><a4_0/> was abolished in the federal courts by the adoption of the Federal Rules of Civil Procedure in <b8_0>1938<b8_0/>; it has also been independently abolished by legislative acts in nearly all states. The Delaware Court of Chancery is the most prominent of the small number of remaining equity courts.
